         <abstract>
            <p>Roger Chartier superbly charts some of the major historiographical breakthroughs of the postwar period and critically explores such issues as narrativity, objectivity, and readership. His chosen authors are Norbert Elias, Hayden White, Philippe Aries, and Louis Marin - to name a few - but this group and their methodologies suggest an identitarian history and historiography that Chartier condemns at the outset. Such an identitarian history, when designated as universal, has costs. The question remains of forging a history, as Thierry put it, of everyone written for everyone.</p>
         </abstract>
